column1041: Strengths of didactic year include passionate, caring, supportive professors who are well-educated experts in their field of study.
column1042: Weakness of didactic year includes a rigorous schedule that called for multiple exams in the same week.
column1043: Clinical year offered many sites to choose from and worked to set up new sites if desired. I also enjoyed having 3 electives to gain experience in sub-specialties.
column1044: It would be beneficial to have physical exam reviews in the simulation lab on call back days in addition to the lectures that are provided.
column1045: Simulation labs are VERY helpful. It would be beneficial to practice more scenarios during lab time opposed to just a typical "cardiac physical exam" have it be more specific such as "chest pain physical exam".

column1041: The didactic curriculum is in-depth and intensive. It challenged me to learn all the important information needed for clinical year. The anatomy sessions (not dissection) were enough to learn important structures while still having time to study other topics. I found not having dissections to be a strength of the program. The faculty are wonderful. They are interested in teaching and animated about subject material.
column1042: The only weakness I would point out is some classes taught by visiting professors did not meet expectations and did not provide me with the information that I needed to know on that given topic.
column1043: Clinical rotations were fabulous. 10/11 of my rotations I would go back to. I liked that the rotations were 4 weeks in length. It was enough time to feel comfortable in the rotation and learn, but short enough to have a lot of different rotations. Callback days once a month when we returned to school were useful in the information reviewed.
column1044: The only weaknesses I experienced during my clinical year had to do with the rotations individually and not the program's clinical curriculum.
column1045: OSCEs and standardized patients utilized by the program were helpful in applying knowledge and receiving feedback. It would have been beneficial to start these during first year rather than second year. Simulation labs, during which we practiced physical exam skills on classmates, were helpful in preparing me for clinical year. Spending time at the student clinic was greatly beneficial in learning how to take a history, perform an exam, and write a progress note.

column1042: '- The schedule 8:00am-5:00pm of lectures is not conducive to productive learning. I am very confident that I would have learned much more and would have been a much better student if I had more time to teach myself the material (rather than sit in lecture) and then apply that knowledge in class.  - Need more practice with imaging, EKGs, oral presentations, SOAP notes - While the lecturers were very intelligent, many (especially physicians) gave way too much information that we did not need to know. They need to focus their lectures to applicable information.  - I would have liked lecturers to address whether diagnostics tests were initial vs gold standard (as we are asked this on the PANCE) - Anatomy was too long (several months) and it would have been more helpful if we used dissection opportunities to walk through what some common surgeries would look like rather than just dissecting different organs.  - We had to self-teach dermatology  - Exams were not always as challenging as I expected.

column1044: '- Faculty would not take my request for my elective seriously enough.  - Faculty told me I was trying to do too much (in terms of seeking out opportunities to learn and practice skills). I thought it was inappropriate and discouraging for them to essentially tell me to try less and be a worse student.  - I was more than willing to travel anywhere in order to get the best experience possible. However, I was stuck within a half hour from campus where nothing happens. This caused me to gain way less experience than I had wanted and expected.  - Many other students complained about having to travel so far for rotations whereas others, such as myself, were happy to travel. Whenever we suggested switching rotations with another student (even if it was the same field of medicine), the faculty became very upset with us. I understand it's a tedious process to set up rotations, but if two students agree that the other's rotation will serve them better, that change should be made.   - I feel that I missed out on many networking and/or job opportunities simply because my faculty did not want to place me in the rotations I requested. Yes, I say did not WANT to because they ended up placing other students in my requested locations even though those students did not care as much about that rotation as I did.

I wish I had the time and patience to express how deeply unsatisfied and displeased with the amount of unprofessionalism and poor academic guidance I have received at this university. The bottom line is that the individuals employed do not care about the students as they so adamantly advertise upon acceptance into this program. Professors use their positions of power to belittle and degrade students, of which I have never seen at a professional institution. The information taught during didactic year is outdated and worthless in the clinical setting. The facilities and labs are overcrowded and overused. I would never recommend this program and it's a shame that it still has the audacity to call itself a place of education. This institution needs to take a stern look at itself and re-evaluation what it is at the core because frankly in it's current state it is a festering hole of necrotic filth.

column1042: Half thought out system based education.  Bringing on new faculty without any experience in being an educator.  Faculty that like to intimidate and "bully" students.  As an educator your "legacy" is the success of your students.  It seems they have it backwards and always want to try to maintain the status quo in their favor at all times.  There are a lot of gaps in knowledge from pathophysiology, biochemistry, and lab medicine.  There wasn't an underlining connection to this new and improved education and grading made absolutely no sense.  The faculty couldn't even explain what "acceptable pass completion" was.  Oh i thought it was a little weird that our program required ACLS and BLS, but we couldn't get it on our own ut had to go through the directors own llc company to be certified.  Odd but conflict of interested perhaps.  I guess people don't care and just causally give accreditation to those that look good on the outside and smooth talkers.
